2 Principle

2.1 Definition

Cluster analysis/Clustering:
A simple and intuitive method of data simplification. It splits a number of observations or measured variables into groups that are similar in their characteristics or behaviors. It focuses on the classification of the quantify data, and is a kind of unsupervised learning.
Cluster:
a group of objects such that the objects in the cluster are closer (more similar) to the âcentreâ of their cluster than to the centre of any other cluster. The centre of a cluster is usually the centroid, the average of all the points in the cluster, or the most ârepresentativeâ point in the cluster.
Hierarchical Cluster Analysis:
Based on the core idea that objects are more closely related to nearby objects than to more distant ones. Two methods: 1. Agglomerative (bottom-up) approach: each observation starts with its own cluster and if pairs of clusters are close enough, they are combined into one. It then moves up in the hierarchy until the results of the clustering meet a pre-determined criterion. 2. Splitting method (top-down): all observations start with a single cluster and are split recursively as they move down the hierarchy.
Centroid-based Cluster Analysis:
The clusters are represented by a centroid vector or a centroid. The centroid vector or centroid is not necessarily part of the data set. A data value is assigned to a cluster depending on its proximity, which means that it has the smallest squared distance from the centroid vector.

2.2 Methods

2.2.1 K-means

Centroid models:
Iterative clustering algorithms. With each iteration, they correct the position of the centroid of the clusters and also adjust the classification of each data point.
K-mean:
Classify a given data set by a certain number (K) of predefined clusters. The most common centroid-based clustering algorithm.

Advantages:

  1. The fastest centroid-based algorithm.
  2. Work for large data sets.
  3. Helps in reducing the intra-cluster variance measure.

Disadvantages:

  1. Performance is affected when there is more noise in the data.
  2. Outliers can never be studied.
  3. Even though it reduces intra-cluster variance, it canât affect or deal with the global minimum variance of measure.
  4. It is very sensitive at clustering data sets of non-convex shaped clusters.

The most commonly used implementation of k-means clustering is one that tries to find the partition of the n individuals into k groups that minimises the within-group sum of squares over all variables.

In fact, the numbers involved in the calculations are so large that it would be impossible to make a complete enumeration of every possible partition, even with the fastest computers.

Table 1. Number of possible partitions depending on the sample size n and number of clusters k.

Steps:

  1. Specify the number of clusters required denoted by k.
  2. Assign points to clusters randomly.
  3. Find the centroids of each cluster.
  4. Re-assign points according to their closest centroid.
  5. Re-adjust the positions of the cluster centroids.
  6. Repeat steps 4 and 5 until no further changes are there.

2.2.2 Hierarchical cluster analysis

Suitable for clustering of small data sets because of the cost on time and space.

Advantages:

  • The similarity of distance and rules is easy to define and less restrictive.
  • There is not required to specify the clustering number in advance.
  • It can discover the hierarchy of clusters, showing by the tree.

Disadvantages:

  • The algorithm is complex.
  • It does not scale well, because of the difficulty of choosing merging or splitting points.

Approaches:

  • Agglomerative (AGNES): Begin with each observation in a distinct (singleton) cluster, and successively merges clusters together until a stopping criterion is satisfied.
  • Divisive (DIANA): Begin with all patterns in a single cluster and performs splitting until a stopping criterion is met.

3 Workflow

3.1 Data and question

  • Same unit â- because of the ignoring of physical meanings, focusing on number.
  • Same dimension â- because of the measuring of distance.
newIris <- iris[1:4]

3.2 The kmeans method

Compare the Total Within Sum of Square under different k values. Determine the optimal clustering number.

library(factoextra)
fviz_nbclust(newIris, kmeans, method = "wss")

Set k = 3. Clustering.

kc <- kmeans(newIris, 3)

Create a cross tabulation of clustering and original species to Check the results.

table(iris$Species,kc$cluster) 
            
              1  2  3
  setosa     50  0  0
  versicolor  0 48  2
  virginica   0 14 36

Visualization.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(newIris[c("Sepal.Length", "Sepal.Width")],
     col = kc$cluster,
     pch = as.integer(iris$Species))
points(kc$centers,
       col = 1:3,
       pch = 16,
       cex = 2)
plot(newIris[c("Petal.Length", "Petal.Width")],
     col = kc$cluster,
     pch = as.integer(iris$Species))
points(kc$centers,
       col = 1:3,
       pch = 16,
       cex = 2)

Box-Cox transformation:
A flexible data normalization method which can minimize the skewness. More suitable for the (applied geochemical and) general environmental data. The data for Box-Cox transformation is required to be positive and continuous variables1.

    However, we can use agglomerative coefficients (AC) to compare the strength of the hierarchical clustering structures.

    Agglomerative coefficients (AC) is used to measuring the clustering structure. The stronger the clustering structure, the higher the agglomerative coefficient (closer to 1).(aka âdivisive coefficientâ for DIANA)

    library(cluster)
help("coef.hclust")
coef.hclust(hc)
coef.hclust(hc2)

    Both agglomerative coefficients are small, it is because agglomerative coefficient grows with the number of observations. And the hierarchical clustering structure which the distance measure is âcanberraâ has higher agglomerative coefficients, so it is stronger.

    Data Preprocessing:

    # Normalization by BOX-COX
library(forecast)
iris.trans = BoxCox(as.matrix(iris[,-5]), lambda = "auto")
library("cluster")
#Perform AGNES
irisHcA = agnes(iris.trans, metric = "euclidean", method = "average")# The default setting
#Cut the AGNES tree at cluster number(k) = 3
hclusterA <- cutree(irisHcA, k = 3)
tb1 <- table(true = iris$Species, cluster = hclusterA)
tb1
                cluster
true          1  2  3
  setosa     50  0  0
  versicolor  0 46  4
  virginica   0 50  0
    #Extract the agglomerative coefficient. When using agnes/diana(), it's automatically calculated
irisHcA$ac# k value will not affect the agglomerative coefficients
    [1] 0.9378719
    #Perform DIANA
irisHcD = diana(iris.trans, metric = "euclidean")# No linkage method, default setting
#Cut at k = 3
hclusterD <- cutree(irisHcD, k = 3)
tb2 <- table(true = iris$Species, cluster = hclusterD)
tb2
                cluster
true          1  2  3
  setosa     50  0  0
  versicolor  0 46  4
  virginica   0  3 47
    #Extract divisive coefficient
irisHcD$dc
    [1] 0.9555297

    Both of the coefficients are much larger than that in the previous part and close to 1, so both of the clustering structures are strong. And itâs obvious that diana()âs result has larger coefficient(so the clustering structure is stronger) and the different (better) separation result.

    It may be because: We use a larger dataset this time. And divisive clustering(DIANA) is a process that gradually splitting the whole into clusters(up to down), so is good at identifying large clusters. Agglomerative clustering (AGNES) is good at identifying small clusters (down to up).

    However, agnes() and hclust() can use different linkage methods. And changing the linkage method can affect the clustering result.

    For example, change the linkage method to single(-linkage):

    #change the linkage method
irisHcS = agnes(iris.trans, method = "single")
hclusterS <- cutree(irisHcS, k = 3)
tb3 <- table(true = iris$Species, cluster = hclusterS)
tb3
                cluster
true          1  2  3
  setosa     49  1  0
  versicolor  0  0 50
  virginica   0  0 50
    irisHcS$ac
    [1] 0.8807232

    Although the clustering structure is weaker and the separation situation is still not good, the clustering result is very different from when using âaverageâ. It is because the linkage method is used to measure the distance between every two clusters, (usually) the larger the cluster, the greater the linkage methodâs influence.
